What are the Different data types in C#?
C# has two types of data types — value types and reference types. Value types like int, float, double, bool, char, struct, and enum store data directly and live on the stack. 
Reference types like class, array, interface, and delegate store a reference to data on the heap.
String is an exception — it's technically a reference type, but since it's immutable, it behaves like a value type."


What is the difference between class and struct?"
"The main difference is that class is a reference type and struct is a value type.
A class is allocated on the heap, and the variable holds a reference to it. So when I pass a class object to a method or assign it to another variable, both variables point to the same object — any change through one reflects in the other.
A struct is allocated on the stack, and it holds the actual data. So when I assign a struct to another variable or pass it to a method, a completely independent copy is created — changes in one don't affect the other.


const is a compile-time constant, value fixed at declaration, implicitly static. readonly is a runtime constant, value can be set at declaration or in constructor, and can differ per instance. 
static means the member belongs to the class, shared across all instances, and its value can still change unless combined with const or readonly.

What are delegates? (with example)"
"A delegate is a type-safe function pointer — it holds a reference to a method and lets me call that method through the delegate, or pass it around like a variable."
public delegate int MathOperation(int a, int b);
public int Add(int a, int b) => a + b;
public int Subtract(int a, int b) => a - b;

// Step 3: Assign method to delegate and invoke
MathOperation op = Add;
int result = op(5, 3);   // result = 8



What are events in C#?
An event is a way for a class to notify other classes or objects when something happens, using the publisher-subscriber model. 
Internally, events are built on top of delegates — an event is basically a delegate with restricted access, so outside code can only subscribe or unsubscribe to it, but can't directly invoke 
it or overwrite other subscribers.
