What is a lambda expression?
A lambda expression is a shorthand way to write an anonymous method — a method without a name — using the => syntax, called the 'goes to' operator. It makes the code more concise and readable,
especially when I'm passing a small piece of logic as a parameter, like in LINQ queries or delegates.

List<int> numbers = new List<int> { 1, 2, 3, 4, 5 };
var evenNumbers = numbers.Where(n => n % 2 == 0).ToList();


Explain LINQ.?
"LINQ stands for Language Integrated Query. It's a feature in C# that lets me query data — from collections, databases, XML, or any data source — using a consistent, 
SQL-like syntax directly in C#, instead of writing separate query logic for each data source.
List<int> numbers = new List<int> { 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6 };

var evenNumbers = numbers.Where(n => n % 2 == 0)
                          .OrderByDescending(n => n)
                          .ToList();

// Output: 6, 4, 2

IEnumerable executes the query in memory — on the client side. So if I'm querying a database using IEnumerable, it first pulls all the data into memory, and then applies the filtering, sorting, etc.
This is suited for querying in-memory collections like List or Array.

IQueryable executes the query on the data source itself — like the database. It builds an expression tree and translates it into SQL, so filtering, sorting, and paging all happen at the database level, 
and only the final result is brought into memory. This is more efficient for querying large datasets from a database using Entity Framework.

IEnumerable<Employee> emp1 = dbContext.Employees.ToList();
var result1 = emp1.Where(e => e.Salary > 50000);

// IQueryable - filtering happens in the database itself
IQueryable<Employee> emp2 = dbContext.Employees;
var result2 = emp2.Where(e => e.Salary > 50000);


What are Extension Methods?
Extension methods let me add new methods to an existing type — including built-in types or types I don't own the source code for — without modifying the original type or creating a new derived type.
They're defined as static methods in a static class, and the first parameter uses the this keyword to specify which type is being extended.
public static class StringExtensions
{
    public static bool IsValidEmail(this string str)
    {
        return str.Contains("@") && str.Contains(".");
    }
}

// Usage - looks like it's a built-in method on string
string email = "test@gmail.com";
bool result = email.IsValidEmail();   // true


What are Generics?
Generics let me write a class, method, or interface that works with any data type, without specifying the exact type in advance. Instead, the type is provided when I actually use it — this gives type 
safety at compile time and avoids boxing/unboxing, while also letting me reuse the same code for different data types.
class Box<T>
{
    public T Value;
}

Box<int> intBox = new Box<int>();
intBox.Value = 10;

Box<string> strBox = new Box<string>();
strBox.Value = "Hello";

What is async await in .net?
async and await are keywords in C# used to write asynchronous code. They allow long-running operations — like database calls or API calls — to run without blocking the main thread. 
So while that operation is in progress, the main thread is free to do other work, keeping the application responsive. Once the operation completes, execution resumes from where it left off,
usually on a thread pool thread.


what is request pipeline?
When a request comes in, Kestrel — the built-in web server — receives it first, then hands it off to the middleware pipeline. Each middleware component gets a chance to inspect or modify the request,
do some work, and then either pass it to the next middleware using next(), or short-circuit the pipeline and return a response immediately without going further.

What is Kestrel?
Yes, exactly right. Kestrel is the web server that receives the HTTP request first — it's the entry point of an ASP.NET Core application. Once Kestrel receives the request,
it hands it off to the ASP.NET Core middleware pipeline, which then processes it through the various middleware components — like exception handling, routing, authentication, 
authorization — before finally reaching the controller/endpoint that generates the response

What is RestAPi ?
REST API is an architectural style used to design web services that communicate over HTTP. Every resource — like an Employee or Order — is identified by a unique URL, and clients interact with
these resources using standard HTTP methods: GET to retrieve, POST to create, PUT to update the entire resource, 
PATCH to update it partially, and DELETE to remove it http methods like get/put/post patch/delete

What are HTTP methods?
Interview Answer — "What are HTTP methods?"
HTTP methods, also called HTTP verbs, define the type of action a client wants to perform on a resource identified by a URL. They're the foundation of how REST APIs work — each method maps to a specific 
operation like creating, reading, updating, or deleting data


Database First :-
In Database First, the database already exists — maybe created by a DBA or an existing legacy system — and I generate my C# entity classes automatically by scaffolding them from the existing database schema.
Code First :- 
In Code First, I start by writing C# entity classes, and EF generates the database schema from those classes using Migrations. This is the approach I use most often, especially in new projects, because it keeps the database
schema in sync with the code — I write my model, run a migration, and the database gets created or updated automatically.


What is DbContext?
DbContext is the main class in Entity Framework Core that represents a session with the database. It's the bridge between my C# code and the actual database —
I use it to query data, save changes, and manage the connection, all through this single class
DbContext automatically tracks changes made to entities I've retrieved — like if I fetch an Employee and modify its Salary property, DbContext knows this object has changed, even before I call SaveChanges()
Each DbSet<T> property inside DbContext represents a table in the database. I query and manipulate data through these DbSets.

what is DbSet<T>?
DbSet<T> represents a collection of entities of a specific type — basically, it maps to a table in the database. Each DbSet property inside my DbContext corresponds to one table, and I use it to query, add, 
update, or delete records for that entity

