Difference between lazyloading and eager loading?
Lazy Loading means related data isn't loaded until I access it — the navigation property needs to be marked virtual, and I need to enable UseLazyLoadingProxies(). It's inefficient because accessing related data
for multiple records fires separate queries for each one — the N+1 query problem. Eager Loading, using .Include(), loads everything upfront in a single SQL query with a JOIN — so I get the main entity and its 
related data together in one round-trip, which is much more efficient.


What is explicit loading?
Explicit Loading means related data is NOT loaded automatically — I have to write code myself to explicitly load it, exactly when I want. It's similar to Lazy Loading in that the related data isn't fetched with 
the main query, but instead of it loading automatically the moment I access the property, I manually trigger the load using a specific command


What is tracking vs notracking?
By default, EF Core tracks every entity it retrieves from the database — this is called Tracking. Tracking means EF Core keeps a record of the entity's original state in memory, so it can detect any changes made to it later and generate the correct SQL when I call SaveChanges(). NoTracking tells EF Core NOT to keep track of these entities — useful when I only need to read data and won't be updating it."
Tracking (Default behavior)
When I query data normally, EF Core automatically starts tracking each entity returned. It stores a snapshot of the original values internally in something called the Change Tracker.





